May's stage
London —— Faced with a daunting task, Britain's new Prime Minister Theresa May must implement the will of British voters — or, more precisely, those of England and Wales — to leave the EU and manage the far-reaching consequences of this work.
This challenge she faces outshines those of recent predecessors.
But she may have the ability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who has demonstrated courage in a series of crises, all the tools needed to accomplish the task are in May's hands.
She is clever and resilient, and she has no patience for nonsense.
She possesses a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
Unbound by any ideology, she is very adept at exercising control, operating within self-defined boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues at hand.
In most battles she has been involved in, May has emerged victorious, showing no mercy to those who have used underhanded tactics against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — one that she needs to exploit fully to lead the Brexit process.
The Brexit process has already begun, there can be no doubt about that.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to stay in the EU, May has repeatedly said that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has consistently stated that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers all agree with her view.
But May has yet to provide a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is extremely challenging.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
It would be hard to know exactly what you will actually be eating.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some may be primarily concerned with preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others may be more focused on gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order every item on the menu.
The reality that Brexit advocates often overlook is that the EU will not give Britain anything for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win hearts and minds or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (though such inflammatory rhetoric is sometimes heard, as Boris Johnson, Britain’s new foreign secretary, said of “Hitler-style imperialism”).
Rather, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has their own political or commercial interests to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine what Britain’s goals should be in negotiations with the EU (and the world in terms of trade) based on reality.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that need separate discussions), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are finished, my granddaughter who is currently 11 might be starting university!)
We must prioritize to avoid extending the negotiation period any further.
The goal is to balance access for British exports and services (especially financial services) into other European countries with restrictions on EU citizens entering the UK.
Gains in one area will require greater concessions in another.
May needs to skillfully leverage the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation outcomes.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that dissatisfaction is not limited to just one segment – such outcomes are inevitable – but extends to all.
This will intensify another major challenge facing May's government: bridging the growing divide in British society exposed by Brexit.
Blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, long estranged from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called agents of globalization – the EU.
The big cities of England – especially London – may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have received no benefits.
Due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn, many blue-collar workers became prey to the populist Brexit promises.
"We will reverse globalization," they claimed.
"We will drive out immigrants who depress wages and divert hundreds of millions of pounds that would have gone to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would return Britain to a safer and more prosperous past.
The Brexiteers could not deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, and cutting immigration from the EU is impossible.
Any such move would only harm British businesses.
Even if economic downturns reduce migration, workers who voted for Brexit may still feel disenchanted with low-paying jobs and strained public services.
This is unlikely to boost social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already unleashed an uncontrollable populist mood storm.
Just as Donald Trump has been unable to improve the circumstances of American working-class voters, Brexit will fail to deliver benefits to those who chose it, no matter how things appear.
Though it has many advantages, this challenge may still be one that May cannot overcome.
